`tikzpicture` wrapped in `figure` environment
```
>>> print(nx.to_latex(gn, as_document=False))
\begin{figure}
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    ...
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{figure}
```


### Expected Behavior

There is no extra environment around `tikzpicture`. Indeed, the latter may be used without an extra wrapper, or there can be
several `tikzpicture` in a `figure`. Literal programming systems such as [SageTeX](https://ctan.org/pkg/sagetex) provide ways to invoke Python from TeX macros, e.g. something like the following
```tex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz} 
\usepackage{sagetex} 

\begin{document}

\begin{sagesilent}
 import networkx as nx
 g=graphs.PetersenGraph().networkx_graph()
\end{sagesilent}

Here is my favourite graph:
\sagestr{nx.to_latex(g, as_document=False)}

\end{document}
``` 
should, after processing, give a pdf with the picture of Petersen graph after the text,
not placed somewhere `figure` thinks is appropriate.

### Steps to Reproduce

Take your favourite graph as `gn` and call `print(nx.to_latex(gn, as_document=False))`

### Environment

Python version: 3.9.2
NetworkX version:  3.0


